“This is a roadmap — you need to dive deep into each topic on your own”
1. Basic Syntax & Type System

• var vs final vs const: var is inferred and mutable, final is assigned once, const is a compile-time constant

• Type Inference: Dart infers the type automatically in most cases

• Sound Type System: Dart’s static type system is guaranteed at runtime as well
var name = "John"; // inferred type (String)
final age = 28; // assigned once, then immutable
const pi = 3.14159; // compile-time constantint counter = 0; // explicit type annotation2. Null Safety

• ?: a nullable type indicating a variable may be null

• !: non-null assertion — throws a runtime error if null

• ?? and ??=: providing/assigning a default value when null

• late: a variable initialized later but marked non-null
String? name;int length = name?.length ?? 0; // 0 if null
int forced = name!.length; // error if nullname ??= "Default Name"; // assign only if nulllate String apiKey; // assigned later, guaranteed non-null
apiKey = "secret-key";3. Functions

• Positional/Named/Optional Parameters: {required this.x}, [optional] parameter types

• Arrow Functions: single-expression functions using =>

• Functions Are First-Class Citizens: they can be assigned to variables and passed as parameters
String greet(String name, {String message = "Hello"}) {
return "$message, $name!";
}greet("Jane"); // "Hello, Jane!"
greet("Jane", message: "Hi"); // named parameterint double(int x) => x * 2; // arrow functionvoid Function(String) logger = (message) => print("[LOG] $message");4. Control Flow

• switch: gained pattern-matching support in Dart 3, can enforce exhaustive checks

• for-in & Iterable: looping over collections

• Collection if/for: adding elements conditionally or with a loop while defining a list/map
String describe(Object x) => switch (x) {
int n when n > 0 => "Positive number: $n",
String s => "Text: $s",
_ => "Unknown",
};final list = [
1, 2, 3,
if (true) 4, // collection if
for (var i in [5, 6]) i * 10, // collection for
];5. Classes & Objects

• Properties: field definitions, customizable via getters/setters

• this: the this.field shortcut in constructor parameters

• Class Modifiers (Dart 3): keywords like final, sealed, interface, base that constrain class behavior
class User {
final String id;
String name; User(this.id, this.name); // constructor shortcut String get shortName => name.substring(0, 3);
}sealed class Shape {} // Dart 3: restricted set of subclasses
final class Circle extends Shape {} // final: can't be extended outside this library6. Constructor Types

• Named Constructor: alternative constructors like User.empty()

• Factory Constructor: doesn’t always have to return a new instance, can contain logic

• Redirecting Constructor: a constructor that forwards to another constructor
class User {
final String id;
final String name; User(this.id, this.name); User.empty() : this("0", "Unnamed"); // redirecting constructor factory User.fromJson(Map<String, dynamic> json) {
return User(json['id'], json['name']); // conditional/processed creation
}
}7. Mixins

• mixin: “mixing” behavior from multiple classes, Dart’s approach to multiple inheritance

• with: the keyword for applying a mixin to a class

• on: restricting a mixin to only be usable on a specific type
mixin Flyable {
void fly() => print("Flying!");
}mixin Swimmable {
void swim() => print("Swimming!");
}class Duck with Flyable, Swimmable {} // gets both behaviorsfinal duck = Duck();
duck.fly();
duck.swim();8. Extension Methods

• extension: adding new functionality to an existing type — even ones you didn’t write
extension IntExtensions on int {
int get doubled => this * 2; bool get isEven2 => this % 2 == 0;
}print(5.doubled); // 10
print(4.isEven2); // true9. Abstract Class & Interface

• Abstract Class: a base class that can’t be instantiated directly, carrying shared behavior

• implements: in Dart, every class implicitly acts as an interface — implements requires every member to be rewritten

• abstract interface class (Dart 3): explicitly marking classes intended only as interfaces
abstract class Storage {
void save(String data);
}class FileStorage implements Storage {
@override
void save(String data) => print("Saved to file: $data");
}abstract interface class Loggable {
void log(String message);
}10. Inheritance & Polymorphism

• extends: inheriting from a single class

• @override: redefining a method from the superclass

• super: accessing the superclass’s implementation
class Shape {
double area() => 0.0;
}class Circle extends Shape {
final double radius;
Circle(this.radius); @override
double area() => 3.14159 * radius * radius;
}final shapes = <Shape>[Shape(), Circle(3)];
for (final s in shapes) print(s.area()); // polymorphism11. Generics

• Generic Classes & Functions: structures that take a type parameter

• Bounded Types: constraining a generic type, e.g. <T extends Comparable>
class Box<T> {
final T content;
Box(this.content);
}T larger<T extends Comparable<T>>(T a, T b) {
return a.compareTo(b) > 0 ? a : b;
}final stringBox = Box<String>("hello");
final intBox = Box<int>(42);12. Collections & Functional Operations

• List, Set, Map: Dart’s core collection types

• map, where, reduce: chaining functional transformations

• Spread Operator (...): unpacking a collection's elements into another collection
final users = [
{'name': 'Alice', 'active': true},
{'name': 'Bob', 'active': false},
];final activeNames = users
.where((u) => u['active'] == true)
.map((u) => u['name'])
.toList();final list1 = [1, 2, 3];
final list2 = [0, ...list1, 4]; // [0, 1, 2, 3, 4]13. Closures & Higher-Order Functions

• Anonymous Function: an unnamed function like (x) { return x * 2; }

• Closure: a function’s ability to “capture” variables from the scope where it’s defined

• Higher-Order Function: a function that takes or returns another function
Function makeCounter() {
int count = 0;
return () {
count++; // captures 'count' from the enclosing scope
return count;
};
}final counter = makeCounter();
print(counter()); // 1
print(counter()); // 2int apply(int x, int Function(int) operation) => operation(x);
print(apply(5, (x) => x * x)); // 2514. Cascade Notation (..) & Other Operators

• Cascade (..): chaining multiple method calls on the same object without repeating it

• Null-aware Cascade (?..): a safe cascade when the object may be null

• Spread & Null-aware Spread: operators used for merging collections
final buffer = StringBuffer()
..write("Hello")
..write(", ")
..write("World!"); // each line operates on the same bufferprint(buffer.toString()); // "Hello, World!"15. late & static

• late: guarantees a variable is initialized later but will be non-null

• late final: a variable assigned only once, but lazily

• static: members tied to the class, not to an instance
class DataManager {
late final List<int> heavyData = _compute(); // runs only on first access List<int> _compute() {
print("Computing...");
return List.generate(1000, (i) => i * i);
} static int instanceCount = 0; // shared across all instances
}16. Enum (Enhanced Enums)

• Classic Enum: a fixed set of values

• Enhanced Enum (Dart 2.17+): enums that can carry constructors, methods, and properties
enum Direction { north, south, east, west }enum Planet {
mercury(mass: 3.3e23, radius: 2439.7),
earth(mass: 5.9e24, radius: 6371.0); final double mass;
final double radius; const Planet({required this.mass, required this.radius}); double get gravity => mass / (radius * radius);
}17. Records & Pattern Matching (Dart 3)

• Record: an anonymous, immutable structure carrying multiple values together without defining a class

• Destructuring: breaking a record or object into its components

• Pattern Matching: resolving data structures with switch and if-case
(String, int) userInfo() => ("Alice", 25);final (name, age) = userInfo(); // destructuring
print("$name, age $age");({String name, int age}) namedRecord = (name: "Bob", age: 30);if (userInfo() case (String n, int a) when a >= 18) {
print("$n is an adult");
}18. Error Handling

• try/catch/finally: Dart’s error handling syntax

• throw: any object can be thrown as an error

• Exception vs Error: distinguishing recoverable situations (Exception) from programming mistakes (Error)
class NetworkError implements Exception {
final String message;
NetworkError(this.message);
}String fetchData(bool hasConnection) {
if (!hasConnection) {
throw NetworkError("No connection");
}
return "data";
}try {
print(fetchData(false));
} on NetworkError catch (e) {
print("Network error: ${e.message}");
} finally {
print("Operation complete");
}19. Async/Await & Future

• Future: a data type representing a single asynchronous operation that will complete in the future

• async/await: writing asynchronous code that reads like synchronous code

• Future.wait: running multiple Futures in parallel and waiting for all to complete
Future<String> getUser(String id) async {
await Future.delayed(Duration(seconds: 1)); // simulates a network call
return "User $id";
}Future<void> main() async {
final user = await getUser("1");
print(user); final results = await Future.wait([
getUser("1"),
getUser("2"),
]); // runs in parallel
}20. Stream

• Stream: an asynchronous data source that emits multiple values over time

• StreamController: manually adding data to a stream

• Stream Operators: processing a stream with map, where, listen
Stream<int> emitNumbers() async* {
for (var i = 1; i <= 5; i++) {
await Future.delayed(Duration(milliseconds: 100));
yield i; // each value reaches the listener when emitted
}
}void main() {
emitNumbers()
.where((n) => n % 2 == 0)
.listen((n) => print(n)); // 2, 4
}21. Isolates

• Isolate: Dart’s thread-like unit of parallel execution with no shared memory

• compute(): a Flutter helper function for running heavy work on a separate isolate

• Messaging: data between isolates is shared via copying/messages rather than references
int heavyComputation(int n) {
var result = 0;
for (var i = 0; i < n; i++) result += i;
return result;
}Future<void> main() async {
final result = await Isolate.run(() => heavyComputation(1000000000)); // runs on a separate isolate
print(result);
}22. Extension Types (Dart 3.3+)

• extension type: a lightweight wrapper giving a type a new “view” with no runtime cost

• Type Safety: turning primitive types (e.g. int) into meaningful, distinguishable types
extension type UserId(int value) {
bool get isValid => value > 0;
}void getUser(UserId id) {
print("Fetching user: ${id.value}");
}getUser(UserId(5)); // a meaningful type is used instead of a plain int23. Testing

• test package: Dart’s official unit testing framework

• group and setUp: grouping tests and defining shared setup code

• Mocking: creating fake dependencies with mockito or mocktail
import 'package:test/test.dart';void main() {
group('Calculator', () {
late Calculator calc; setUp(() {
calc = Calculator();
}); test('two numbers should add up', () {
expect(calc.add(2, 3), equals(5));
});
});
}24. Package Management

• pubspec.yaml: the manifest file defining dependencies, SDK version, and assets

• pub.dev: the official repository for Dart/Flutter packages

• dart pub get / upgrade: commands for downloading and updating dependencies
name: my_package
environment:
sdk: '>=3.0.0 <4.0.0'dependencies:
http: ^1.2.0
meta: ^1.15.0dev_dependencies:
test: ^1.25.025. Other Things You Should Know in Production

• Sound Null Safety: as of Dart 3, the entire language is fully compliant with null safety

• Tree Shaking: unused code is automatically eliminated during compilation

• dart compile: compiling Dart code to a native executable, JS, or an AOT snapshot

• Dart DevTools: the official analysis tool for inspecting memory, performance, and the widget tree
// dart compile exe main.dart → produces a native executable
// dart compile js main.dart → produces JavaScript for th
